"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78619","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of people aged 50-64 in work has risen by over 300,000 in the last year. This is likely to reflect the recovery in the economy together with the effect of welfare reform and the equalisation of state pension age. There are nearly 150,000 fewer people aged 50-64 without a job than a year ago. Some of this has been reflected in lower economic inactivity, as more people enter or remain in the labour force, but unemployment and long-term unemployment have also fallen on the year.</p><p> </p><p>On 13 June 2014, the DWP published Fuller Working Lives - A Framework for Action</p><p>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-framework-for-action" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-framework-for-action</a>) which explains how working longer can benefit individuals, businesses, society and the economy. It sets out a number of new actions to help people have fuller working lives. A Business Champion for older workers has also been appointed, tasked with making the case for older workers within the business community and challenging outdated perceptions.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78619/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-21T14:37:01.6252598Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78619/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78619/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Unemployment: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the reasons for trends in long-term unemployment among people over 50.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","206172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78620","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-22","<p /> <p>We have no plans to carry out such an estimate. As referenced in the earlier answer from the former Minister of State for Disabled People, the Rt. Hon. Member for Hemel Hempstead (Mike Penning), most people claiming Personal Independence Payment (PIP) will already be receiving some element of financial support to meet day-to-day living expenses. If entitlement to PIP is established, payment will be backdated.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78620/answer","Forest of Dean","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78620/answer/previousversion/11775","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78620/answer/previousversion/11775","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","2014-07-22T11:21:58.4503603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78620/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78620/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2014, Official Report, column 110W, on personal independence payment, if he will estimate the number of people who do not currently claim disability living allowance who go into debt while their claims for personal independence payment are pending.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","206201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78621","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-21","<p /> <p /> <p>The information is not available.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78621/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-21T15:51:55.1646189Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78621/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78621/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Employment Schemes: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many Youth Contract wage incentive payments made since April 2012 have related to work activity of (a) over 30 hours' duration and (b) between 16 to 29 hours' duration per week.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","206168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78622","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-21","<p /> <p /> <p>The information requested is not readily available and there would be a disproportionate cost to collate this information.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78622/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-21T16:01:00.832541Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78622/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78622/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Flexible Support Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many jobseekers were supported through the Flexible Support Fund in 2013; and what proportion of such were (a) men, (b) under 25 years old and (c) over 50 years old.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","206169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78623","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-22","<p /> <p /> <p>Current resource data shows a full time equivalent of 465 staff currently working on the Universal Credit Programme.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78623/answer","Forest of Dean","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78623/answer/previousversion/11777","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78623/answer/previousversion/11777","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","2014-07-22T11:24:39.344942Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78623/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78623/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many officials are currently working on the universal credit programme.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","206235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78624","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-22","<p /> <p /> <p>The requested information is not available.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78624/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T11:45:02.2296787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78624/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78624/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Social Security Benefits: Perth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of households in Perth and North Perthshire constituency whose incomes from benefit payments have reduced by (a) 10 per cent, (b) between 20 and 49 per cent and (c) 50 per cent or more since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Pete Wishart","Perth and North Perthshire","Pete Wishart","206252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78625","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-22","<p /> <p /> <p>The publication of any new statistics series needs to ensure that it is based on robust data and the measures reflect the system that is being delivered and latest performance. The Department’s statisticians are currently looking at developing measures around clearance times and will pre-announce future publication in line with the UK Statistics Authority protocols.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78625/answer","Forest of Dean","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78625/answer/previousversion/11785","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78625/answer/previousversion/11785","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","2014-07-22T11:12:35.8247735Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78625/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78625/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 July 2014, Official Report, column 278W, on personal independence payments, what his Department's definition is of a mature system; and how he proposes that the maturity of the system will be measured.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","206342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78626","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-22","<p /> <p /> <p>The full rate of the new State Pension will give an income above the basic means test, rewarding retirement income saving.</p><p> </p><p>It is estimated that in 2020 around 10% of pensioner households receiving the new State Pension, around 200,000 benefit units, in Great Britain would be eligible for the Savings Credit element of Pension Credit if it had not been removed for people who reached State Pension age after the introduction of new State Pension in April 2016.</p><p> </p><p>By 2030, it is estimated that 15% of the new State Pension households, around 1 million benefit units, would be in this position.</p><p> </p><p>Not all of these people would take up their eligibility to Savings Credit. The Department estimates that take-up amongst people eligible for only the Savings Credit element of Pension Credit is between 43% and 48%.</p><p> </p><p>Breakdowns of the impact analysis by country or region within Great Britain are not available.</p><p> </p><p>It is estimated that retaining Savings Credit for all pensioners and uprating it line with earnings would lead to additional annual costs in the UK of around £2bn in 20 years' time.</p><p> </p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78626/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T11:49:29.1204573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78626/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78626/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Pension Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the impact assessment of the single-tier pension published in October 2013, if he will make an estimate of how many people reaching state pension age after implementation of the single-tier pension in (a) the UK and (b) Scotland would have been eligible for savings credit in (i) 2020 and (ii) 2030 had savings credit not been abolished.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","206369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78627","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-07-22","<p /> <p /> <p /> <p>The requested information is not available from current Management Information systems as no information relating to the causes of call terminations is gathered. As such, it is not possible to distinguish between reasons for termination or to distinguish between calls terminated by agents or callers.</p><p>The current Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) policy is that all calls should be free to our 0800 numbers to claim:</p><p> </p><ul><li>State Pension;</li><li>Pension Credit;</li><li>Jobseekers’ Allowance;</li><li>Income Support;</li><li>Employment Support Allowance; and,</li><li>Personal Independence Payment.</li></ul><p> </p><p>It is free to call DWP 0800 numbers from all major landline providers.</p><p> </p><p>DWP continues to have agreements with O2, Everything Everywhere (formerly Orange and T-Mobile), Vodafone (including Cable &amp; Wireless), Three (also known as Hutchison 3G), Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile ahead of the OFCOM changes due in June 2015. This agreement allows many of our customers to make free mobile phone calls from their participating networks to the Department’s 0800 customer numbers.</p><p> </p><p>DWP is aware of possible concerns about call charges to enquiry and claims lines so agents will routinely offer to call a customer back if concerns are raised over the cost of the call. The Department also provides controlled access to telephones for claimants if required in support of job-searches or benefit enquiries.</p><p> </p><p>During June 2014 the average duration of a call to the Primary Benefit New Claims lines (ESA, IS and JSA) from connection to termination was 14 minutes and 43 seconds.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78627/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T12:18:43.6384181Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78627/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/78627/answer",,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-07-16","Social Security Benefits: Preston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on how many claims for benefits made by telephone by people in Preston constituency in 2014 to date were interrupted by the claimant running out of credit.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mark Hendrick","206310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79201","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p>As the Prime Minister said in his comprehensive statement yesterday, we are clear that Israel has a right to defend itself against these attacks. No country would stand by as rockets are fired or terrorist tunnels are constructed into their territory. We are equally clear that Israel’s response must be proportionate, taking all necessary steps to minimise civilian casualties in line with International Humanitarian Law.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79201/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T14:23:55.5135685Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79201/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/79201/answer",,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-07-16","Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the situation in Israel and Palestine.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","905000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77828","Attorney General","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p>No such applications have been made so far.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77828/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T12:11:22.903623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77828/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77828/answer",,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-07-15","Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many applications for a preliminary hearing for a Deferred Prosecution Agreement (a) the Director of Public Prosecutions and (b) the Serious Fraud Office have made since 24 February 2014.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","North East Fife","Sir Menzies Campbell","205838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77829","Attorney General","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p>The Treasury Solicitor’s Department (TSol) does not hold a register of duplicate payments. Appropriate controls are in place to prevent duplicate payments and if any are identified, action is taken to recover overpaid monies. As at 18 July 2014, there are no known unrecovered duplicate payments.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Identification of the value of duplicate payments made by TSol, the Attorney General’s Office and HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate since 2010 would require detailed analysis of accounting and other records which would incur disproportionate cost. However, in the 3 months since April 2014, TSol have identified and recovered duplicate payments with a total value of £13,068 representing 0.05% of the value of payments made during this period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Available records show that, since April 2010, the Serious Fraud Office has identified and recovered £46,000 in duplicate supplier payments. No other duplicate payments have been identified.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the value of duplicate payments identified by the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) since 2009/10 and the proportion of such payments recovered in each of the last two financial years is presented below.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Duplicate Payments and Recoveries 2009-2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Duplicate payments</p></td><td><p>£135,958</p></td><td><p>£256,803</p></td><td><p>£72,729</p></td><td><p>£91,578</p></td><td><p>£149,124</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Recovered proportion</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>96.2%</p></td><td><p>98.8%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Mr Robert Buckland",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77829/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T12:14:09.0756656Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77829/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77829/answer",,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2014-07-15","Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what the value is of duplicate supplier payments identified by the Law Officers' Departments since 2010; and what proportion of such payments have since been recovered in each of the last two financial years.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","205965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77830","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-22","<p>Sharia law has no jurisdiction in England and Wales and the Government has no intention to change this position.</p><p> </p><p>The legal profession is independent of Government and is regulated by approved regulators for which the Legal Services Board has oversight responsibility. The Solicitors Regulation Authority (SRA) is the independent regulatory arm of the Law Society, the approved regulator for solicitors under the Legal Services Act 2007. The SRA has advised that its recent guidance issued on the drafting and preparation of wills relates to conduct issues concerning the drafting and preparation of wills, rather than their content. At the end of that guidance, reference was made and links attached to other sources of information, amongst which was a link to the practice note issued by the Law Society. The SRA advise that such references are regularly attached to their guidance and are not an endorsement of their content. The SRA advise that the reference to the Law Society practice note has now been removed from the appendix to its guidance note.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77830/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T16:51:32.7867261Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77830/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77830/answer",,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-15","Legal Systems: Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Solicitors Regulation Authority is continuing to endorse the Law Society practice note on Sharia succession rules; and whether such an endorsement is compatible with the SRA's obligations under the Equality Act 2010; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","205890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77831","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-10","<p>The Export Refinancing Facility (ERF) was launched on 30 April 2014 in order to support UK bids for projects that require finance above £50m.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The ERF does not provide funds directly to firms but a commitment to banks funding loans to overseas buyers of UK exports to take-out that loan if it has not been possible for the bank to refinance it commercially.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>UK Export Finance officials have held several discussions with exporters, overseas buyers and banks in relation to ERF, with one case currently under discussion.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>It is likely that ERF will be most relevant during periods of constrained liquidity in the banking market. Given current market conditions, export credit transactions are less likely to require ERF in order to take place but the facility remains an important product in UKEF’s portfolio giving it the ability to respond quickly to changes in those market conditions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77831/answer","West Suffolk","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77831/answer/previousversion/11695","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77831/answer/previousversion/11695","Biography information for Matt Hancock","2014-10-10T12:28:30.280353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77831/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77831/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Exports: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many bids to the Export Refinancing Facility have been (a) received and (b) approved since its launch; and how many firms have received funds under the scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77832","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-22","<p>The allocations to pilot fishing investors was finalised for all these investors on 8 October 2013.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77832/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T14:26:56.2235727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77832/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77832/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Royal Mail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to his letter of 2 May 2014 which was placed in the Library, on what date agreement was reached with each of the pilot fishing investors in Royal Mail on share allocations.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77833","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p>a) No staff in BIS are currently working full time on the issue of Sunday Trading. There are two policy staff and one lawyer that have Sunday Trading as part of their wider portfolio e.g. providing briefing on policy and employment aspects, answering PQs, drafting responses to Bill amendments and information requests, providing correspondence advice. In addition there are 2 staff that deal with standard correspondence some small proportion of which will include responding to letters referring to Sunday Trading legislation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>b) We are not aware of any staff in Executive Agencies of BIS that are specifically assigned to work on the issue of Sunday Trading.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77833/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T13:41:30.2284411Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77833/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77833/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Sunday Trading","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many staff (a) in his Department and (b) its executive agencies are currently working wholly or in part on the issue of Sunday trading.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77834","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-09-10","<p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There has been significant interest in UK Export Finance’s (UKEF) Direct Lending Facility (DLF) since its enhancements were announced in the Budget. Since it was relaunched on 30 June 2014, the pipeline of potential export contracts has developed and now involves 28 UK-based exporters of varying size and export experience. As it stands, the pipeline has 35 potential export contracts that range from £3m to over £350m. Most importantly, the DLF pipeline is growing.</p><p> </p><p><br> <br></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77834/answer","West Suffolk","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77834/answer/previousversion/11686","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77834/answer/previousversion/11686","Biography information for Matt Hancock","2014-09-10T15:33:12.7257872Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77834/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77834/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Business: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many firms have received assistance under the Direct Lending Scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77835","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-10","<p>Maintaining and updating the Royal Mail shareholder register is the responsibility of the company.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A number of financial market Information providers publish information about company shareholders including Royal Mail.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold any information that cannot be obtained from these sources.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77835/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-10-10T12:26:46.6200862Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77835/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77835/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Royal Mail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what information his Department  holds on the current ownership of shares in Royal Mail.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77836","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-15","<p>No assurances were sought from the priority investors ahead of the sale of shares in Royal Mail.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Any mechanism which requires a buyer to give up the rights normally associated with shares, such as a restriction on the right to sell those shares for a period of time, would be reflected in the price investors would be prepared to pay for those shares.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These investors gave the Government confidence to take forward the IPO which raised nearly £2bn for the tax payer and reduced the risk that the tax payer to support the universal postal service.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77836/answer","West Suffolk","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock","Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77836/answer/previousversion/11677","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77836/answer/previousversion/11677","Biography information for Matt Hancock","2014-10-15T13:24:04.1152597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77836/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77836/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Royal Mail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assurances were sought from priority investors ahead of the privatisation of Royal Mail on long-term holding of shares by (a) Ministers in his Department (b) Officials in his Department (c) the Financial Adviser to the Government and (d) the banking syndicate working on the privatisation.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77837","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-08-28","<p>The Department has not made an assessment regarding this issue.</p><p>If there is evidence that treating emails in this manner is driving anti-competitive behaviour by companies, this should be referred to the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA), the UK’s independent competition authority, for consideration.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77837/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-08-28T15:43:56.7989475Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77837/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77837/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Business: Email","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the financial advantages enjoyed by larger companies in preventing their marketing and promotional emails from being blocked by servers.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bingham","High Peak","Andrew Bingham","205876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77838","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills has not received any direct representations from representatives of the secondary ticketing websites on amendments tabled to the Consumer Rights Bill or about the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013 and the Department for Business Innovation and Skills’ guidance on them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Neither my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State nor other Ministers in the Department for Business Innovation and Skills have had meetings with the secondary ticketing websites about the implementation of the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013 or the Department for Business Innovation and Skills’ guidance on them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The draft Regulations and the contents of the Bill were widely consulted on and the Department received a range of comments in response. Officials from the Department have also had discussions with a wide range of stakeholders (including with secondary ticketing websites) on the implementation of those Regulations and the guidance on them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following a consultation on the draft regulations, the Department for Business Innovation and Skills has produced guidance on the requirements of the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013. This guidance is easily accessible on the gov.uk website. Officials have also worked with the Business Support Helpline, which offers free advice to business on a wide range of issues, including regulation, and with the Trading Standards Institute (TSI), as the primary body responsible for educating businesses on consumer law. TSI has also produced guidance which is available on their website. Consumers themselves are important in driving compliance and officials have worked with Citizens Advice to raise consumer awareness so that they can see when businesses are not abiding by the requirements of the regulations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business Innovation and Skills has also actively promoted the changes in the Regulations across all sectors through seminars, presentations and communications to businesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Ministers in the Home Office, Department for Culture Media and Sport and the Department for Business Innovation and Skills have discussions and correspond together on a wide range of issues, and this has included agreeing the content of the Consumer Rights Bill. Officials from those Departments are in regular contact, including regarding the issue of resale of tickets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","205806 ; 205807 ; 205808 ; 205864","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77838/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-21T14:17:11.4450706Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77838/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77838/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Tickets: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations he received from representatives of secondary ticketing websites on the guidance to or implementation of the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","205818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77839","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-22","<p>The Department does not maintain a central register but an analysis of the Departmental financial system and records identified that since 2010, the following duplicate payments were made and recoveries undertaken:</p><p>10/11 nil</p><p>11/12 nil</p><p>12/13 £726 of which all was recovered</p><p>13/14 £1835.40 of which all was recovered</p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77839/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T14:52:08.8846895Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77839/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77839/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the value is of duplicate supplier payments identified by his Department since 2010; and what proportion of such payments have since been recovered in each of the last two financial years.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","205964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77840","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-22","<p>The UK became an observer member of the SESAME Interim Council in 2001. Professor Samar Hasnain of Liverpool University has represented the UK Government at the SESAME Council, following his appointment in 2004. The Government has provided funding since 2008/9 to Professor Samar Hasnain to support his role as the UK’s representative on the SESAME council as follows:</p><p>- 2008/9 – 2013/14: £15k per annum</p><p>- Additional funding of £22k per annum was recently approved following a review of the project for the financial years 2014/15 – 2015/16</p><p>Professor Samar Hasnain in his role as an observer undertakes various activities on behalf of the Government for the progress of SESAME including:</p><p>- Representing the Government at the Interim Council meetings</p><p>- Producing an annual report on SESAME and its benefits to the UK; and</p><p>- Spreading awareness of the existence and desirability of SESAME to existing and potential SESAME member countries.</p><p>He is also an active member of the Science Advisory Committee which meets twice a year.</p><p>This Department does not currently fund any other collaborative scientific research projects between Israel, Iran and the Palestinian Authority.</p>","Tunbridge Wells","Greg Clark",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77840/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T14:44:15.9260365Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77840/answer","Biography information for Greg Clark","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77840/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Research: Middle East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assistance the UK has given to the developments of the SESAME (Synchrotron-light for Experimental Science and Applications in the Middle East) project; and what collaborative scientific research projects the UK supports between Israel, Iran and the Palestinian Authority.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","205936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77841","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","true","2014-09-10","<p><ins class="ministerial">Farnborough is an important showcase for the UK aerospace sector. The Department does not make estimates of aerospace exports arising as a result of the Farnborough Airshow. However, given the UK’s position as a leading supplier to the world’s aerospace industry, our industry is likely to be a major beneficiary of many of the new orders announced at the Show.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Recent data from the Aerospace Defence and Security trade association show aerospace exports grew by 12% in 2013 to £25 billion.</ins></p><p><br /><del class="ministerial">There has been significant interest in UK Export Finance’s (UKEF) Direct Lending Facility (DLF) since its enhancements were announced in the Budget. Since it was relaunched on 30 June 2014, the pipeline of potential export contracts has developed and now involves 28 UK-based exporters of varying size and export experience. As it stands, the pipeline has 35 potential export contracts that range from £3m to over £350m. Most importantly, the DLF pipeline is growing.</del></p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77841/answer","West Suffolk ; West Suffolk","West Suffolk ; West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock ; Matthew Hancock","Matthew Hancock ; Matthew Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77841/answer/previousversion/11700 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77841/answer/previousversion/19350","Biography information for Matt Hancock ; Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77841/answer/previousversion/11700 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77841/answer/previousversion/19350","Biography information for Matt Hancock ; Biography information for Matt Hancock","2014-09-10T15:27:30.573Z","2014-10-29T14:19:01.5130846Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77841/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77841/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Trade Fairs: Farnborough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what estimate he has made of the net benefit to the UK export sector as a result of the recent Farnborough Airshow.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","206009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77842","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-15","<p>Employment tribunal remission data extracted in its current form from HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service (HMCTS) systems has not yet been assured to sufficient standards to provide the number of remission applications received, subsequently awarded, in full or partial.</p><p> </p><p>The number of awards each month is available from financial information relating to fees and remissions in the employment tribunals system published by HMCTS in its Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p> </p><p>The number awarded each month from July 2013 to June 2014, the most recently published reporting period, is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Employment Tribunal (ET)</strong></p><p><strong>Remission Volumes<sup>1</sup></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>ET Remission Volumes</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2013</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2013</p></td><td><p>92</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2013</p></td><td><p>107</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2013</p></td><td><p>261</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2013</p></td><td><p>193</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2013</p></td><td><p>144</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2014</p></td><td><p>379</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2014</p></td><td><p>114</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2014</p></td><td><p>753</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14 Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2044</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2014</p></td><td><p>503</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2014</p></td><td><p>754</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2014</p></td><td><p>612</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>July 2013 to June 2014 Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,913</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong><sup>1</sup></strong>Timing differences exist between data uploaded to the finance system and data entered at source within employment tribunals fees systems. The monthly profile shown here reflects the date remissions were recorded on the finance system. This may not reflect the date on which remission applications were received or processed. The year end total for remissions granted is materially accurate.</p><p> </p><p>The Annual Report and Accounts for 2013-14 was published in June 2014 on the Ministry of Justice website and can be found at:</p><p>http://www.justice.gov.uk/publications/corporate-reports/hmcts.</p><p> </p><p>The Employment Tribunals Fees &amp; Remission case management system records fees paid and remissions awarded and was introduced in July 2013. However, the system does not record the amount of time for assessing each individual fee remission and it is not, therefore, possible to calculate the average and total aggregate costs.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77842/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-10-15T15:29:26.1575069Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77842/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77842/answer",,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-15","Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many applications for remissions relating to fees for employment tribunal proceedings have been (a) made and (b) awarded in each month since July 2013; and what has been the (i) average cost of assessing each claim and (ii) total aggregate cost to the public purse of making such assessments.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77843","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-08-28","<p>No agreement was sought from the priority investors ahead of the sale of shares in Royal Mail on the long term holding of shares.</p><p>Any mechanism which requires a buyer to give up the rights normally associated with shares, such as a restriction on the right to sell those shares for a period of time, would be reflected in the price investors would be prepared to pay for those shares.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77843/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-08-28T15:23:59.7210667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77843/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77843/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Royal Mail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what agreement was sought from priority investors on the long-term holding of shares in Royal Mail.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77844","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills has not received any direct representations from representatives of the secondary ticketing websites on amendments tabled to the Consumer Rights Bill or about the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013 and the Department for Business Innovation and Skills’ guidance on them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Neither my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State nor other Ministers in the Department for Business Innovation and Skills have had meetings with the secondary ticketing websites about the implementation of the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013 or the Department for Business Innovation and Skills’ guidance on them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The draft Regulations and the contents of the Bill were widely consulted on and the Department received a range of comments in response. Officials from the Department have also had discussions with a wide range of stakeholders (including with secondary ticketing websites) on the implementation of those Regulations and the guidance on them.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Following a consultation on the draft regulations, the Department for Business Innovation and Skills has produced guidance on the requirements of the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013. This guidance is easily accessible on the gov.uk website. Officials have also worked with the Business Support Helpline, which offers free advice to business on a wide range of issues, including regulation, and with the Trading Standards Institute (TSI), as the primary body responsible for educating businesses on consumer law. TSI has also produced guidance which is available on their website. Consumers themselves are important in driving compliance and officials have worked with Citizens Advice to raise consumer awareness so that they can see when businesses are not abiding by the requirements of the regulations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business Innovation and Skills has also actively promoted the changes in the Regulations across all sectors through seminars, presentations and communications to businesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Ministers in the Home Office, Department for Culture Media and Sport and the Department for Business Innovation and Skills have discussions and correspond together on a wide range of issues, and this has included agreeing the content of the Consumer Rights Bill. Officials from those Departments are in regular contact, including regarding the issue of resale of tickets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson","205807 ; 205808 ; 205818 ; 205864","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77844/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-21T14:17:10.8303454Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77844/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77844/answer",,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-07-15","Tickets: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he, Ministers or officials in his Department have had with secondary ticketing websites about guidance to or implementation of the Consumer Contracts (Information, Cancellation and Additional Charges) Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","205806"
