"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77892","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p>We have not undertaken any research yet into the effects of the 2010 changes to the ventilation provisions in Part F of the Building Regulations, but this is being considered by the Department.</p><p> </p>","Bristol West","Stephen Williams",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77892/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T13:41:07.2549944Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77892/answer","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77892/answer",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-15","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what research he has undertaken into the effects of the changes introduced in 2010 to Part F of the Building Regulations.","true","Biography information for Mr Nick Raynsford","Greenwich and Woolwich","Mr Nick Raynsford","205935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77893","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-07-22","<p> </p><p>The Future High Streets Forum has met three times this year, on 21 January, 29 April and 8 July. Attendee details can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/future-high-streets-forum" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/groups/future-high-streets-forum</a></p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77893/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-07-22T13:34:57.8881801Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77893/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77893/answer",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-15","Future High Streets Forum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, on how many occasions the Future High Streets Forum has met this year; and who has attended each such meeting.","false","Biography information for Chuka Umunna","Streatham","Mr Chuka Umunna","206018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77894","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-09-03","<p> </p><p>In my Department's publication “50 ways to save”, we asserted that councils could save money by conducting audits of potential duplicate payments and reforming accounts payable processes. This was based on research by Experian of both local and central government bodies.</p><p> </p><p>In the answer by my hon. Friend, the Member for Great Yarmouth (Brandon Lewis) of 5 November 2013, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 145W, it was noted how our Department has itself undertaken such best practice, and had duly recovered £61,301 of taxpayers' money from twenty duplicate payments for the period May 2010 to October 2013, apart from a sum of £257 which was not recoverable from three payments. A further £32,000 was recovered from historic duplicate payments made between 2006 and 2009. I also would note there were £7,018 of duplicate payments from January to April 2010.</p><p> </p><p>Since that answer, our ongoing internal processes have identified a further £7,492 from four transactions from November 2013 to March 2014, all of which have been recovered thanks to our strengthened checks.</p><p> </p><p>We have previously commissioned business analytics and information services firm, PRGX, to carry out a full spend-recovery audit on our accounts payable system and help us further improve and reform administrative practices. PRGX’s audit report has subsequently noted that 99.999% of the transaction value reviewed was processed correctly, and that: &quot;DCLG have been effective in limiting supplier overpayments. The low rate of errors identified by the audit and statement request process indicates the current processes and controls continue to limit supplier overpayments.&quot;</p><p> </p><p>This sizeable saving endorses what we said in “50 ways to save”: regularly checking for duplicate payments and putting systematic checks in place is a common-sense way of saving taxpayers' money in both local and central government.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77894/answer",,,,,,,,,"2014-09-03T14:16:14.0540046Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77894/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77894/answer",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-15","Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the value is of duplicate supplier payments identified by his Department since 2010; and what proportion of such payments have since been recovered in each of the last two financial years.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Mr Tom Watson","205967"
